**Reviewed:** the Matt Smith Type 7 draft. It's well-built — the physio-room cold open, the felt-interior beat at 16, and the Morbius empathy turn are genuinely strong, and I flagged those as keepers.

**The two biggest issues I raised:**

1. **The case rests almost entirely on his role choices** (which characters he plays) plus a handful of interview quotes — but those choices are shaped by directors and agents too. The draft never faces a skeptic's obvious objection: *you've diagnosed his casting, not the man.* It needs at least one beat anchoring the Seven read in his off-screen behavior. That counterargument is currently buried in the Rabbit Hole; it belongs in the main body.

2. **His personal life is almost completely absent** — the biggest reader-expectation gap. Two things a Matt Smith reader expects and won't find: the [Crown equal-pay controversy](https://tvline.com/news/the-crown-matt-smith-pay-gap-controversy-claire-foy-netflix-938651/) (he out-earned lead Claire Foy and publicly backed her getting paid equally — a rare on-record look at his values and loyalty), and his long relationship with Lily James. Five straight sections of role analysis with no relational life makes it feel like a piece about an actor, not a person.

I also noted some trims: the spine/spondylosis image and the door/room/exit metaphor cluster are both load-bearing but over-repeated, and "the grief gets a costume" refrain lands near-verbatim twice — keep the intro and ending instances, thin the middle echoes so the final payoff stays sharp.

No body edits made, per the command — feedback only.

